         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>One of a set of the nine Muses for which a number of other bases survive 
               (cf. Goodchild, Libya Antiqua III-IV (1966-7) 259, against Mingazzini, L'Insula di Giasone Magno, 73f.<!--check-->) but are uninscribed, 
               cf. the set found the Theatre 3: <ref type="inscription">C03800</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C03900</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C04000</ref>, 
               <ref type="inscription">C04100</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C04200</ref>, <ref type="inscription">C04300</ref> . 
               If the building is correctly regarded as the official residence of the gymnasiarch (see <ref type="inscription">C02900</ref>), the Muses were presumably chosen because of their connexion with παιδεία. For their association with gymnasia see H. Siska, De Mercurio ceterisque deis ad artem gymnicam pertinentibus (Diss. Halle, 1933) 44.</p>
         </div>
         
